column168: On April 1, 2020 at 1930 EST, XPO Logistics notified ERTS of a UN2991 "Lannate LV" release at their terminal. They reported that a 2.5 gallon poly jug released its contents due to a puncture caused by the previous terminal. ERTS dispatched Hepaco to conduct all on site cleanup activities. At 2222 EST, contractors arrived on site and confirmed approximately 1 gallon of product released to a 4' x 6" area of the trailer floor from one jug. All impacted jugs were removed from their boxes, wiped down, and re-palatalized for shipment. The damaged jug and all cleanup debris were containerized into (2) 55 gallon poly drums and staged on site for terminal personnel to manage.
RESPONDER NOTIFIED OF LEAKING HAZMAT DISCOVERED IN UPS FACILITY.

On April 2, 2020 at 0135 EST, ERTS was contacted by XPO Logistics Terminal XCO to report a spill. The terminal stated that  a 55 gallon metal drum of UN1993 Bonderite C-MC STC 104 was punctured by a forklift releasing its entire contents to the floor of trailer 317-8697 and to the concrete below the trailer. ERTS dispatched First Call Environmental to conduct all cleanup activities. At 0246 EST, contractors arrived on site and confirmed the release of 55 gallons of product to a 20' x 8' area of the trailer floor and a 47' x 37' area of the concrete below the trailer. Absorbents were laid out and worked into the impacted areas and then collected. All cleanup debris was containerized into (5) 55 gallon metal drums. The damaged drum was then over packed into an 85 gallon metal drum. All waste was left on site for terminal personnel to manage.
The cause of release was reportedly due to damage by forklift.

column168: On 04/04/20 at around 0230 hours EST CSXT personnel reported a possible hazmat release from tank car AZXX32317, residue Flammable Liquid, N.O.S. (Crude Sulfate Turpentine), in Rice Yard, Waycross, GA. The car was isolated and the shipper, Kraton (Debbie Busken; 904-307-8977 debbie.busken@kraton.com). Hull’s Environmental, a CSXT response contractor, responded and also detected a strong odor of turpentine coming from the car.  Upon further investigation Hull’s discovered that the nozzle gasket was deteriorated causing a vapor release. The issue identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper, Kraton.  Hull’s installed a new nozzle gasket and secured the manway therefore securing any further vapor release.  The car was released.    NAR Cause Code: 209 – Manway gasket deteriorated  5(4+3+0) x (2+0) = 70 NARRI   Waycross, GA AZXX32317, Flammable Liquid, N.O.S (Crude Sulfate Turpentine)

column168: Veolia employees determined that the 55-gallon drum was leaking while off-loading a truck at  Veolia's 10 day in-transit facility in Schenectady, NY. Approximately 5 gallons of material leaked  from the container. Upon closer inspection it was identified that there were three small punctures  in the bottom of the drum most likely caused by a nail that was on the floor of the box truck. The  box truck was inspected at its home office prior to heading to the 10-day facility in Schenectady  and there were no signs of a leak at that time. It is believed that the bouncing of the vehicle on  the trip to Schenectady and the nail on the floor of the box truck caused the punctures in the  drum. The trained Veolia, Schenectady employees donned the appropriate PPE, overpacked the  leaking container and cleaned up the spill.
column169: On 4/6/220, the Veolia EHS Manager required that all vehicles in the district are swept and checked  for nails or other sharp objects that could damage containers. Also, to check any possible screws or  nails that may be sticking into the cargo carrying portion of the truck. Ensuring that there are no loose objects on the floor of any of the trucks will prevent a recurrence of this type of incident.

On April 07, 2020 at 1630 EST, XPO Logistics notified ERTS of a Hypochlorite Solution release at a customers location. It was reported that the product released from a 55 gallon poly drum due to puncture caused by a shipper as they were loading cargo onto the trailer. The release impacted the trailer floor and leaked to the ground below. ERTS dispatched ERS of OK to conduct cleanup operations. At 1745 EST, contractors arrived on site and contained and cleaned the release with absorbents. They confirmed approximately 15 gallons of product released to the trailer and asphalt. All cleanup debris was then containerized into (2) 55 gallon poly drums. The damaged drum was over packed into a 95 gallon poly drum. All waste was then transported to XPO Logistics terminal located in Glenpool, OK.

On April 1, 2020, at 0006 ET, ERTS was contacted by XPO Logistics Terminal LDA regarding a cargo release.  It was reported that due to a forklift accident, (1) 55-gallon plastic drum of DFQ (Corrosive liquid, basic, organic, n.o.s., UN3267) was punctured, releasing approximately 10 gallons of product on to the dock floor.  A contractor was dispatched to clean up the release using absorbents and the proper PPE.  All waste debris generated was containerized in (1) 95-gallon poly drum and (1) 55-gallon poly drum.  The waste drums were then staged onsite at OS&D for terminal personnel to manage.

The tank car was observed to have leakage from the bottom outlet valve cap by Hazardous Materials Manager Tom Robinson and FRA inspector Lester Rawls. Manager Robinson closed the opened valve and secured the cap properly. The spillage was mediated and no further action was needed.

The tank car was reported leaking by UPRR yard personnel. Hazardous Materials Manager Tom Robinson was called to respond. Manager Robinson discovered the car was leaking from the liquid valve mounting flange bolts being less than wrench tight. Manager Robinson tightened the bolts and the leak stopped. The shipper is requesting an OTMA for the car to continue to be home shopped for a proper repair.

column168: At 0733 EST, XPO Logistics Terminal XSB notified ERTS of a release of Ammonia, anhydrous from a cylinder on trailer 311-4741. It was stated that upon opening the trailer the release was discovered and the initial cause was unknown. ERTS dispatched Hepaco to conduct a site assessment. At 1126 EST, contractors arrived on site and advised that there was a heavy odor coming from the trailer. The cylinders were observed to be approximately 6' tall and 1' in diameter. The back of the trailer was opened and an air monitor was used in the trailer.  Contractors applied a soapy solution to the cylinder caps and no leak was observed and advised monitor readings were normal in the trailer. Contractors left the trailer open to continue to ventilate as it was estimated to be residual odor. Contractors advised that the tops of all the cylinders appeared to be tight and departed site with no waste generated. It was undetermined how much product released to the trailer as well as cause of release.
column172: Cylinder, a pressure vessel for compressed gases

column62: Impact with Sharp or Protruding Object (e.g., nails)
column168: On April 17, 2020 at 1722 EST, XPO Logistics notified ERTS of a hazardous product release in one of their trailers at their terminal located in Fridley, MN. ERTS dispatched EnviroServe to conduct on site cleanup. At 1743 EST, contractors arrived on site. Upon unloading the trailer the contractors were able to determine the release of three products. Contractors confirmed a total of approximately 10 gallons released to the trailer floor and approximately 5 gallons to the concrete below the trailer. Various neutralizing agents were used to neutralize the trailer floor then absorbents were placed down to soak up the loose materials. Once completed the contractors moved onto the concrete area where neutralizing ash, and absorbent material was used. These were worked in with brooms and collected. All three drums were each containerized into a 95 gallon over pack along with cleanup debris. All waste was left on site for terminal personnel to manage.

column168: As freight was being loaded at the origin terminal, one of the drums was slightly over-hanging the skid. As the skid of drums were slid forward, they hit a protruding piece of metal on another skid causing the drum to be punctured. The drum was immediately turned on it's side and placed into an overpack to prevent further release. The released material was neutralized and cleaned with absorbent material. All of which was placed into the overpack for later disposal. Due to the danger of material, the package specifications were not able to be obtained.
column169: This incident may have been prevented if proper dunnage was placed in front of the skid with protruding metal. The employee involved in this incident was disciplined in accordance with company policy. This incident may be used in future safety meetings to illustrate the importance of proper dunnage to protect freight.

column168: On 04/21/20 at around 2120 hours EST CSXT personnel reported a hazmat release from tank car UTLX125822, loaded Sulfuric Acid, in Rice Yard, Waycross, GA. The car was isolated and the shipper, Mosaic (Gus Navar; 813.500.6748, Gustavo.Navar@mosaicco.com). Hull’s Environmental, a CSXT response contractor, responded and discovered that the liquid line cap was missing a gasket.  Hull’s reported liquid product released from the top of the car from the liquid line onto the sides of the car and the ground. The issue identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper, Mosaic.  Hull’s installed a new gasket and secured the liquid line cap.  The car was wiped down and area remediated.  The car was released.    NAR Cause Code: 249– Liquid line closure cap  5(5+5+0) x (2+0) = 100 NARRI   Waycross, GA UTLX125822, Sulfuric Acid

Veolia technicians were offloading a truck by way of the lift gate. During unloading, a drum hit into  another drum on the lift gate and knocked it to the ground. The lift gate was wet and slippery because it was raining. The drum landed on the concrete pad and  split on the seam at the top of the drum  resulting in the release of approximately 500-1000 ml. The leaking drum was overpacked into an 85  gallon drum for continued transportation to the destination facility.
column169: The drums were being unloaded by the lift gate versus waiting for the loading dock to become  available due to project time constraints. The technicians have been advised to use the loading dock  when unloading a truck and to work with the loading dock schedule better in the future so that it is  available when unloading.

At approximately 12:40 on April 23, 2020, a puddle was observed under a trailer that was parked at Veolia's 10-day intransit facility located in Henderson, CO. The trailer was unloaded and two 55 gallon  drums were discovered to have a pin hole leak on the bottoms of the drums. Less than 1 gallon total liquid spilled onto the containment pad. The drums were overpacked into salvage containers and the  spill was remediated by trained Veolia personnel. The personnel who responded to the spill reported  that the drums appeared to be in good condition with no identifiable cause of the pinholes in the drums.
column169: As a specific cause was unable to be identified it is difficult to make specific recommendations to  prevent a reoccurrence. Veolia will continue to emphasize the importance of container inspections to employees involved in the transportation of hazardous materials.

column168: On April 6, 2020 at 1000 hours, Mechanical Foreman at the Consolidated Rail River Rouge Yard, River  Rouge (Detroit), Michigan reported that GATX 1959, a loaded tank car of UN2448, Sulfur, Molten, was  leaking around the manway atop of the tank car with a pronounced odor around the immediate area of  the tank car. Reportedly, there was product yellow material around the manway. The tank car was   isolated from Yard personnel. The shipper, Marathon Petroleum Company LP, was notified via direct phone  call to Denise Homan, 606-571-2986 (dmhoman@marathonpetroleum.com). Enviroserve, a Consolidated Rail  emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the River Rouge Yard. Enviroserve found that the release  was caused by a faulty manway ring gasket and improperly secured manway securement bolts. The shipper  was notified of the situation found. The tank car was wiped down and residue sulfur was removed from  around the manway. The tank car was then released back into transportation.  NARRI: 5x(5+1+0)x(2+0) = 60 Cause code: 200/209
UNDECLARED LEAKING PACKAGE DISCOVERED IN UPS FACILITY. NO MARKS OR LABELS ON OUTER CARTON.

Spill was cleaned-up by in-house personnel with driver assistance. Transfer lines were reconnected correctly per established procedure & unloading was completed without further incident.  Root-Cause: Driver error.

Once re-certification is completed, Carrier's Safety Department will review training records & document additional training before releasing driver.

column162: MANAGER OF HAZARDOUS MATERIAL AND ENV.
column168: On April 7, 2020, at 1700 hours, Mechanical Foreman at the Consolidated Rail Port Reading Yard, Port  Reading, New Jersey reported that UTLX 212803, a residue last contained tank car of UN3295,  Hydrocarbons, Liquid was leaking. Reportedly, there was auto-refrigerated product around the BOV  and a gasoline like odor in the immediate area around the tank car. The tank car was isolated from personnel  in the Yard. The Consignee, Markwest Hydrocarbon Inc. was notified directly through their compliance  consultant Harry Hopes (704) 490-1891 hopes@spcigroup.com, since this car originally came from their facility.  Hepaco, a Consolidated Rail emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the Port Reading Yard. Hepaco  found that the leak was caused by a faulty disengaging bottom outlet valve and a less than tool tight bonnet  reducer at the 4" threads. The bottom outlet valve was found to not be completely in the closed position and  allowed the release of the residual product. A wrench was used to tighten the bottom outlet valve and bonnet assembly  into the fully closed position. The shipper representative, Harry Hopes, was notified of the situation found. FRA Hazmat  Inspector Vincent Au was also notified of the defect and subsequent Non Accident Release (NAR) UTLX 212803  was re-inspected the following day to ensure no additional leakage had occurred from the BOV. The valve was  found to be fully closed and no further leakage of product past the ball valve. The FRA notified the tank car  owner and manufacturer of the Disengaging Bottom Outlet Valve to request drawings of the component.   NARRI: 2x(4+5+0)x(2+0) = 36 Cause code:551

On April 28, 2020 at 1824 EST, XPO Logistics Terminal UPH notified ERTS of a UN3265 release while in transit. ERTS dispatched Emergency Environmental Services to conduct all on site cleanup activities. At 1955 EST, contractors arrived on site and confirmed approximately 1 gallon of product released to a 2' x 2' of the trailer floor and top of the tote. The release occurred from the top cap of the tote as well as the bottom valve do to over-pressurizing. A tote transfer was conducted for the salvaged material. The damaged tote was cut up and containerized along with all other cleanup debris into (2) 55 gallon poly drums. All waste was transported to the XPO terminal located in Mesa, AZ for terminal personnel to manage.

column168: a reported single vehicle accident (CTMV rollover) resulting in the reported release of approximately 2500 gallons of UN2586 to the concrete and asphalt roadway. The release reportedly migrated to several nearby storm drains, but was reported to have remained in the catch basins. No soils or waterways were reported as being impacted. The MD DOT applied sand to contain the release. Local first responders placed boom and pads around the drains to limit the migration. Hepaco (environmental contractor) was dispatched to investigate and remediate the release. Hepaco personnel utilized a Lime Solution to neutralize the product. All field testing of the several areas showed pH results of 5-6 at this time. Hepaco personnel utilized heavy equipment, a vacuum truck, hand tools and roll off boxes to collect the impacted sand and debris. Hepaco personnel utilized pads and boom to clean the impacted storm drains. All waste was collected and staged at the MD DOT service lot in Cumberland, MD until waste profiling and disposal could be arranged. Hepaco personnel utilized a vacuum truck to collect the remaining product still in the tanker. The Carrier (MC Tank) provided a replacement tanker. The liquid product collected in the vacuum truck was transferred into the MC Tank replacement tanker and delivered to the consignee.

A Veolia mechanic was drilling screws (1.5" length) into a trailer to install new placards.  While in the  process of installing the placard, he noticed that liquid was dripping out from the trailer. The duration of the spill was approximately 5 minutes and approximately 3 gallons was released. He notified the  Veolia Transportation Coordinator of the release, at which time the tote was moved to the tail end of  the trailer in order to transfer the waste to a new tote.  All contents remaining in tote was transferred  to a new tote.
column169: The screws that the mechanic used to affix the new placards to the trailer were too long which resulted  in puncturing the tote that was loaded inside the trailer. Veolia has re-evaluated its procedure in  regards to repair work. After taking a look at several trailers, we noticed some trailer sides were  thicker than others. For trailers with thicker sides, the screws used would not have gone through but  this particular trailer sides were not as thick. We have re-trained the maintenance group to look inside the trailer prior to working to make sure that all containers are away from the trailers wall in the event  that he needs to screw or mount onto the trailer. In addition, the mechanic was trained and provided  the correct 3/4" length screws to use when mounting placards.

During routine facility operations, material began leaking from a staged transport trailer. In appropriate personal protective equipment, a trained emergency response team entered the trailer to identify the compromised container. As the emergency response team began moving the drums, it became evident the material in the drums was reacting with the steel, thus compromising the containers integrity. Every container was over-packed into an UN specification authorized and compatible container. The contaminated areas were cleaned and remediated thoroughly. The impact of this release was contained to the transport trailer floor and asphalt of the loading facility, with no threat to storm drains, water ways or soil. The drums were sent to their final destination without further incident. A verbal notification was made to Washington State Department of Ecology, who elected to not generate a State Report number and was satisfied with the remediation efforts.
column169: The generator was notified of the incident and began an internal investigation to analyze the root cause. A corrective action of using compatible containers for this waste stream was implemented and notes added to the profile to prevent recurrence.

column168: During switching operations, yard personnel noted a white fog over the top of the car when moving.  A locale contractor responded and investigated the car and found a blown 4.75" 165  psi rupture disc and replaced that disc.  After replacing the rupture disc yard personnel moved the car to a side track and the contractor noted a slight white vapor again but was unable to determine the source.  The contractor and shipper arrived at 0900 the next morning and rechecked the car and found what appeared to be a defective gasket under the rupture disc assembly.  There was no evidence of a release with the car sitting still so the shipper ordered replacement gaskets and returned on 5/1/2020 and replaced all gaskets on the car.  The mounting flange gasket under the rupture disc assembly only had 1/3 of the gasket in place with the remaining 2/3 missing.  Rescar was also onsite and performed a bubble leak test after the repairs were made and no issues were found.  The car was released back into transportation after the test was successful.

column168: On Apil 24, 2020 at 1141 EST, XPO Logistics Terminal NPB notified ERTS of a release of Unisol B-75 from a 55 Gallon metal drum to trailer 425-4346 and the concrete below. The release was cuased by a forklift puncture. ERTS Dispatched Alpha Omega to conduct all on site cleanup activities. At 1605 EST, contractors arrived on site and stated approximately all 55 gallons of the material released. The material was dried in most places and tracked through the parking lot area and dock as well as released to the trailer floor. Contractors used absorbent powder in the trailer and on the dock to absorb any residual product and portland cement on top of it. They also placed the powder and portland on the release that was on the parking lot. The spill was measured at 10' x 36' area in the trailer, 60' x 40' on the dock, 12' x 40' under the trailer and 500' x 25' on the parking lot. Since the majority of the release on the parking lot was already dry, they used portland cement on the stickiest parts. The damaged 55 gallon metal drum was over-packed into a 95 gallon poly over-pack. Contractors departed site at 1907 EST.  On April 27, 2020 at 1126 EST, contractors arrived back on site to complete remediation and try to remove some of the staining. No further action is needed.
NO COMMENTS PROVIDED.

A courier from the LNKA station picked up several packages from the shipper Windstream in Lincoln, NE. There are 204 boxes that were picked up, each with an internal plastic gallon bottle. There were no markings on the bottles, and only FedEx PowerShip(automated airbill) labels on the boxes. There are no DG markings, labels, or declarations with the shipments. However, picking slips in the boxes indicate they contain hand sanitizer but there was no indication of ingredients, no SDS, no brand/ manufacture information. Subsequent information on an SDS received from the shipper indicates the bottles contain hand sanitizer that includes the ingredients Ethanol(79.36%) and Isopropyl Alcohol(3.96%). The shipper stated the product was manufactured by MB Rolland Distillery. The involved packages are 204 individual shipments going to distinct recipient addresses. All of the shipments originated from the same shipper(Windstream), and they are destined for internal Windstream employee use. The packages were scanned to FedEx Consolidation(CONS) tag # 815019894980 to track them aggregately. All of the packages are identical outer fibreboard boxes that hold a single plastic gallon bottle. An example package tracking number from the CdNS is 131720890790. All of the packages were held at the station pending FAA review.

column168: On 4/28/20, FRA Hazmat Inspector Powell found the PROX 39413 to be audibly hissing and noticed an identifiable propane odor when near the housing.  Mr. Powell notified BNSF who isolated the car, made appropriate notifications and inspected the car. BNSF Hazmat identified that a load seal (Ferromex - 4735189) was on the protective housing.  The seal was removed and the inspection revealed that all valve closure plugs (3) were less than hand tight, the sample line plug was entirely out and the thermowell cap was less than hand tight.  A slight leak was observed by snoop to be coming from the vapor plug.  Responders closed the partially opened (1/8 turn) valve and the leak stopped.  All plugs were removed, cleaned and retaped prior to securing to a tool tight condition.  All closures were secured and inspected, the housing was resealed with BNSF seal 539987.  All leaked propane quickly dissipated, estimated release volumes are based upon responders observations and are only rough estimates.

column42: SULFURIC ACID WITH MORE THAN 51 PERCENT ACID
column168: Our driver was travelling eastbound on US-70 hauling sulfuric acid. The driver of a passenger vehicle traveling westbound fell asleep at the wheel and crossed over the center line colliding with our truck and trailer. Our truck and trailer went off the road and our trailer overturned. The overturned trailer was dragged along the road until it came to a stop damaging the rollover protection. This allowed the dome lid/manway area to be impacted by the road. The dome lid/manway breached and all sulfuric acid in the tanker poured out. The tanker drained completely in less than one hour. We immediately called Cura Emergency Services, Kary Environmental and National Interstate Insurance Company to coordinate emergency response and cleanup efforts. The owner of a back-hoe who lived nearby was enlisted by AZ DPS to make burms to contain and direct the acid away from the public roadway.
column169: This was an unfortunate incident caused by the driver of a passenger vehicle who fell asleep at the wheel and crashed into our tractor/trailer. Our driver could not have done anything differently to prevent this accident. It was caused entirely by the at-fault driver who fell asleep at the wheel.

column168: Driver was going down Delaplane Grade Rd when he drifted off the pavement onto the soft shoulder .  The unpaved shoulder of the road was due to recent rain drawing the truck in. The cargo tank remained intact , all leakage of product came from a gasket failure on the dome lid . Product was when a clamp was applied to the dome lid applying pressure to the gasket.  The released was picked up with absorbent materials and all impacted soils were dug up and removed .  Fresh soil was brought in to complete the clean up.
column169: We need to implement better controls to assure the tank components are in proper working order. While this dome gasket showed no signs of failure it had compressed over time and was not making a proper seal.  Routine change out of these gasket seals would have prevented the release.

column43: WASTE WATER TREATMENT SLUDGE F006, D007
column168: Full roll-off container was pulled out from waste water treatment building and being put down into a designated area at the John Deere facility in order to allow the driver to put the empty container under the  waste water treatment building.  While putting the full container onto the ground the material shifted causing material to come out over the top of the container, between the secured tarp and steel roll-off container. Once the driver realized material was coming out of the container he immediately set the container on the ground to stop any additional material from coming out onto John Deere property. Incident review was completed and the root cause was determined to be the first dump of material loaded into the container had a higher moisture content than normal, in turn causing the material to shift when being put down onto the ground.
column169: Meetings were held between Envirite of Illinois Transportation, EH&S,  John Deere Cylinder EH&S and Operations.  It was determined the material put into the container was too wet, caused by the waste water treatment operation.   Customer to communicate problems with filter operations and condition of sludge to driver prior to transport. Driver will have the ability to refuse transport if shipment is too wet.  Customer is discussing the use of temporary and permanent containment areas for the full container to be set down for the exchange with the empty.   Customer to determine viability of installing a system to pump down excess free liquids.  USE will pull the excess liner at the back of the container over the top of the load covering the last two tarp bows before putting the tarp into place, This technique is effective for dusty loads and we anticipate it will also help prevent spillage of loads that are wetter than usual.  Additional straps will be placed around the end of the container to keep the tarp in place, preventing material from leaving the container.

Crews collected all of the impacted Iiquids with a drum vacuum and containerized it within one(1) 55-gallon drum for transport and disposal. column168: Driver was transporting a load of denatured alcohol to Torrance CA to make hand sanitizer for COVID-19 . On 4/19/2020 driver stopped in Sidney NE to get his trucks oil changed and sleep for the night . Driver disconnected the trailer for the oil change .  After oil change driver hooked up trailer and went to sleep. The next morning the driver woke and pre-tripped the truck & trailer. Before leaving the parking lot he did a pull test to next sure trailer and truck were properly connected. Everything was fine. Driver took a left from Upland Pkwy onto on ramp for I-80. When making the turn the trailer became disconnected and rolled over onto an interstate road closure arm. The road closure arm mounting bolts punctured the passenger side of the aluminum trailer. Estimated 2,500 gallons spilled out. Sidney PD and Fire responded to the scene. The public works department brought in a load of sand to spread for containment. Wayne Transports insurance company reported the accident/spill to the State of NE.
column169: Wayne Transports conducted an Root Cause Analysis . We found that while the driver performed his pre-trip inspection and the pull test the driver did not push in on the fifth wheel pin to confirm pin was fully in the locked position.

column168: During an FRA HazMat Inspector initiated inspection, wetness was found on the outside of the manway nozzle.  The following issues were discovered during initial and follow-up assessment:  • Protective housing securement pin was found broken (picture attached) and will need to be replaced. • Manway swingbolt B was found to have impacted/imprinted the manway lid (picture attached), indicative of overtightening and manway lid misalignment over time.  The misalignment could be causing the gap difference between the collar and washer.  We would advise that the manway lid be evaluated further by your team to determine if it may need to be replaced. • The liquid line plug was found less than tool tight and was tightened.    On-site repair was performed by a mobile-repair unit to secure the car, and an OTMA-3 was set for movement of the car to destination for unloading, and then to home-shop for further repairs to the manway securement system.

column168: On April 15, 2020, at approximately 11:00 AM CDT, personnel at the above-referenced R+L Carriers(R+L) terminal were off loading shipments when personnel discovered a damaged 330-gallon tote of a phosphoric acid solution. As a result of the damage, less that one(1) gallon of free product was released onto adjacent cargo. R+L retained Cura Emergency Services, LC (CES) to manage the cleanup. CES dispatched a crew from Hazchem Environmental to assess and remediate. Following a site assessment, Hazchem personnel located one(1) damaged 330-gallon tote that had released less than one(1) gallon of free product onto adjacent cargo. Crews noted it appeared additional cargo was stacked on top of the tote, which combined with a load shift, appeared to be the cause of the release. Hazchem personnel donned the proper personal protective equipment and began to work. Crews neutralized the released free product with sodium bicarbonate and water. All impacted materials were collected and containerized within one(1) 30-gallon poly drum for transport and disposal. Crews utilized a forklift to raise the damaged tote over the new tote and transferred the contents through PVC piping. Once completed, Hazchem personnel released the new tote to R+L personnel and collected the damaged tote for transport and disposal. Crews noted no additional corrective actions were required on-site and demobilized.
When the trailer door was opened the drum fell out onto the apron below the dock.

column168: The corrosive solvent waste was loaded into the tanker on 04/24/2020 and secured on site,  anticipating continued transport to intended waste management.   On 04/26/2020, it was reported product escaped from tanker for approximately twenty minutes.   Facility personnel assembled a response team.  Local Fire Department and Arizona Department of Environmental Quality (ADEQ) arrived on site to monitor events.   Immediate notification provided to NRC - Report Number 1276134. On-site investigation by in-house response team confirmed the tanker failed at the weld on the  tanker gauge.  In-house response team proceeded to close off contaminated area then pumped  the product from the compromised tanker into approved totes.   At this point both the Fire Department and Arizona DEQ stated they were satisfied with the initial  response and left the site.   In addition, all clean-up debris and materials used to decontaminate were collected and placed into the salvage drums. Once complete, the containers were secured and  placed onto the  trailer for continued transportation. Over the next day or so, in-house response team continued to clean the area and remove all  compromised soil.
column169: At the time the container was accepted for transportation, no evidence of damage or leaking was  observed. Drivers will continue to inspect each container during staging period as well as before it is loaded and will take all appropriate actions should a container show evidence of reduced  structural integrity.  IN addition, the shipper has been advised of the situation and have been asked to insure the waste  does not exceed that which it is profiled for.  We have concluded the cause of the release was due to high heat.  We will continue to monitor this product while staged and while in-transit.  Our SOP will include a greater head space in either the  tanker or tote.  Our driver will continue to check his load as prescribed by federal regulations, and  close scrutiny to the pressure monitoring.

column168: On April 22,2020, at approximately 12:30 PM CDT, personnel at the above-referenced R+L Carriers(R+L) terminal were off loading shipments when personnel discovered approximately two (2) gallons of an epoxy activator solution that had released onto the trailer floor and adjacent cargo. R+L retained Cura Emergency Services, LC(CES) to manage the cleanup. CES dispatched a crew from E3 Environmental(E3) to remediate. E3 deployed granular absorbents and pads to the release, then containerized all waste into two(2) 55-gallon drums for transport and disposal. E3 demobilized, noting no further actions required.

A conductor working in the hump yard at CP St Paul Yard reported a strange odor ad hissing noise halfway down track CT38 to the Train Master.  The train Master isolated tracks CT37 though CT41 and kept all employess out of the area. the TM then contacted CP's response team who responded to the yard to investigate the CP response team walked track CT38 and confirmed that CTCX 784061 had a loading rack stub out protruding from the protective housing and that there was odor in the area. the response crew had normal atmospheric readings so they climbed the car and opened the protective housing.  as  the response crew opened the protective housing the odor did increase but atmospheric readings remained normal. the response crew then closed the open vapor valve, removed the stub out and installed the vapor valve plug to tool tight spec. the rest of the valves and fittings were then inspected and found to be closed and tool tight. the protective housing was then re-secured and the car was continued to destination.
column169: the shipper was notified via Chemtrec but never responded. CP Customer Service team also reached out to the shipper to inform them of the incident but they did not respond . CP yard inspectors have been briefed and made aware of the issue with the shipper Yard inspectors will continue to monitor and look for additional issues with the shippers cars.

column168: The CP Yard crew was switching cars at the CP Mason City Terminal on 4/19/2020, At 21:00 hours as the switch crew pulled cars west for head room on the main line the conductor who was standing by the switch smelled a very strong ammonia like odor as the cars pulled west . He immediately moved away from the area and notified the engineer via radio to stop all movement. The conductor then informed the Train Master of the situation and the TM evacuated all yard employees to the Depot building to shelter found no detects on their air monitoring equipment . CP's Response team then swept the area where the odor was initially reported and investigated TILX 500729 the odor grew stronger but no readings were found. the CP response crew continued to investigate the housing and again the odor grew intensity.  The air monitors did get a detect as the response crew continued to investigate the housing but all readings were below action levels.  All of the fixtures and fittings were checked and found to be too tight. the monitor was unable to pin point the source of the leak so ammonia detection tape was used around the valve flanges and along the pressure plate seam. the tape detected product coming from the pressure plate nuts and studs were marked with a wax pencil and impact gun was used to tighten the nuts in a star pattern. after 2 evolutions of star pattern tightening the leak stopped. it was found that the pressure plates nuts had each rotated a 1/4 turn. the housing was then checked again with monitoring tools and all readings were normal . The car was re secured and a verbal OTMA was filed with the FRA. once OTMA was in place the car  was moved to a closer facility for off loading.
column169: CP followed up with the shipper.  The shipper followed up with their loading/unloading teams and additional cars were checked to ensure there were no additional issues.  the shipper also coordinated a Certified Mobile Repair Unit to mobilize to the off load facility to further investigate and certify TILX 500729.

column168: On 4/28/20, FRA Hazmat Inspector Powell found the PROX 39413 to be audibly hissing and noticed an identifiable propane odor when near the housing.  Mr. Powell notified BNSF who isolated the car, made appropriate notifications and inspected the car. BNSF Hazmat identified that a load seal (Ferromex - 4735189) was on the protective housing.  The seal was removed and the inspection revealed that all valve closure plugs (3) were less than hand tight, the sample line plug was entirely out and the thermowell cap was less than hand tight.  A slight leak was observed by snoop to be coming from the vapor plug.  Responders closed the partially opened (1/8 turn) valve and the leak stopped.  All plugs were removed, cleaned and retaped prior to securing to a tool tight condition.  All closures were secured and inspected, the housing was resealed with BNSF seal 539987.  All leaked propane quickly dissipated, estimated release volumes are based upon responders observations and are only rough estimates.

column168: 4 drums were shrink-wrapped on a pallet and picked up at CEM Sales& Service. The pallet was loaded on the right rear of trailer#35008 and strapped to the wall to prevent shifting. Driver departed facility and was driving north on Federal Blvd. when a car driving west on Mississippi Avenue pulled out in front of our driver and forced him to slam on his brakes to avoid a collision. Driver arrived at his next stop which was Game Exchange at 2650 W 6th Avenue in Denver. Upon opening the door driver smelled the pungent odor and noticed one drum Ieaking from the bottom of the drum which appears to be from a nail sticking up in the pallet and was struck when driver slammed on his brakes. Driver called dispatch for instruction and he was told to pull away from customers dock. He pulled ahead approximately 15 feet from the dod( and stopped due to trees and cars being in his way. Driver called Operations Manager Brian Morris to inform him of the spill. Brian called Dan Wita, Safety Director, to inform him of the spill. The drum leaked approximately 15 gallons. column168: On 30 April 2020, 1440 EST, Schneider Bulk Carriers experienced a 100 gallon UN3265, Corrosive liquid, acidic, organic, n.o.s., 8, PGII "BioSoft S-101" release. The cause was undetermined. The released BioSoft S-101  impacted a 15' by 20' area of the concrete parking lot at the customer's location. At 1536 EST, Schneider Bulk Carriers retained Emergency Response and Training Solutions to manage and oversee the above referenced incident. ERTS dispatched Lone Star Hazmat Response, LLC out of Dallas, TX to perform emergency response and cleanup activities. Upon the contractor's arrival and after the site inspection, cleanup operations commenced. The contractor advised prior to their arrival, onsite personnel applied water to the impacted area. Personnel utilized an acid transfer pump to recover the wash liquid into two poly totes. Granular absorbents were then applied to the impacted area of concrete to absorb and solidify any residual material. The contractor recovered the spent absorbents into two poly garbage bags which were later placed into two (2) 55 - gallon poly totes. Lone Star Hazmat Response, LLC personnel then departed the site with the waste generated.

column168: One or the packages in a two-piece MPs shipment was observed to be leaking at the APVA destination station in Costa Mesa, CA. Both pieces were shipped in medium size FedEx boxes. The master package, tracking number 391854001240 became dampened with liquid. The secondary package, tracking 391854001251, was delivered separately before staff could quarantine the entire shipment. The box involved in the spill contained a one quart bottle of Free N Clear cleaner manufactured by Diamond Chemical Co. The cap on this bottle became loose in transit causing the spilled fluid. Per the SDS this commodity is NONDG. However, the package also contained three 10 oz aerosol cans of Lysol Neutra Air Sanitizing Spray. Per the SDS the Lysol spray is classified as UN1950 Aerosols, Flammable. There were no DG markings or labels on the package and no Shippers Declaration was offered with the shipment. The station was directed by Dangerous Goods Administration to have FedEx Spill Cleanup staff contain the shipment and hold it pending further disposition instruction.

The DG Specialist reported that the package in question was investigated under the suspicion of being an undeclared DG shipment . The suspicious were confirmed. While proper packaging was used , the shipment did not have the proper markings, labels , or paperwork, The shipment is being held for the FAA.

column168: The cap broke on one of the package spilled. Inside were four one gallon bottles of hand sanitizer. As this shipment would not meet the criteria to be offered as nonhaz  per  49CFR 173.150 g it is DG. The shipper did not offer the shipment with any DG markings, labels nor a shipper's declaration therefore it is undeclared / hidden DG. Photos were sent to FAA.

At approximately 0651 on April 15, 2020 the  driver was heading  North on I-57 near Ashkum IL. Roads were wet and at the driver came on to a bridge the driver could see a vehicle on the other side of a bridge that had flipped over and was laying on its side in the drivers travel lane. The driver applied the brakes and began to slide jack knifing the tractor trailer and stopping against the opposite traffic barrier. The driver did not the 3rd party vehicle on its side in the road. The tractor's fuel tanks were damaged  and approximately 290 gallons of diesel fuel spilled. Our provider , USEcology , was contacted to clean up the spilled fuel.  They arrived approximately 1430 the same day and were on site for two days to began cleanup. The initial actions stabilized the spill but site remediation has not been completed. The site includes a steep grade and work will need to be done from the shoulder of the roadway. We are awaiting IDOT to issue a lane closure permit to complete the cleanup. The remediation/cleanup cost includes the estimate to complete the work.

column168: Subject Car : PLMX 135540, Empty ( Residue last contained ) UN1075, Petroleum Gases, Liquefied Class 2.1 HAZMAT STCC= 4905752. FRA HAZMAT INSPECTOR AND MYSELF WERE CONDUCTING AN INSPECTION OF TASD INTERCHANGE TRACK 3. DURING THE INSPECTION PLMX 135540 AN EMPTY LPG CAR WAS DISCOVERED TO BE LEAKING VAPOR FROM THE AREA OF THE TANK CAR PROTECTIVE HOUSING. TASD ISOLATED THE CAR, DISPATCHED EMERGENCY RESPONDERS HEPACO  TO THE SCENE TO STOP THE LEAK.  RESPONDERS REMOVED SECURITY SEAL  0004474 FROM THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING AND OPENED IT UP . UNDER THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING THEY FOUND THE CAUSE OF THE LEAK WAS THE A- END AND B-END LIQUID VALVE BEING IN THE OPEN POSITION AND  THE VALVE PLUGS BEING LESS THAN TOOL TIGHT.  THE VAPOR VALVE PLUG WAS ALSO FOUND TO BE LESS THAN TOOL TIGHT . RESPONDERS CLOSED THE OPEN VALVES AND MADE THE LOOSE  VALVE PLUGS TOOL TIGHT , APPLIED A NEW SECURITY SEAL 00315661 TO THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING AND THE CAR WAS RELEASED BACK INTO TRANSPORTATION.

During unloading hose connection camlock fitting unaligned and broke causing material to spill into containment area . Operations shutdown . Hose reconnected and secured . Load was completed without further incidents . Consignee's personnel cleaned-up and processed properly.

column168: One(1) 55-gallon drum containing Toluene was punctured by a nail while in transit inside an R+L Carriers(RLC) unit. RLC retained Cura Emergency Services, LC((DES) to manage the cleanup. CES dispatched a crew from First Call Environmental(FCE) to initiate corrective actions. Following a site assessment, FCE personnel entered the trailer to determine where the release was located. Crews observed a 55-gallon drum on UN1294(Toluene) that had been punctured by a nail at the nose of the trailer. Due to the location of the tractor-trailer on the narrow shoulder, FCE personnel deployed granular absorbent to the freestanding liquid and had the driver move the unit to a safer location for remediation. Once moved, FCE personnel utilized an extendaboom to remove the cargo from the trailer to access the damaged drum. Crews placed the damaged drum in an 85-gallon overpack drum to remove it from the trailer. FCE personnel then collected the granular absorbents from the trailer floor and reloaded the remaining cargo. All UN1294(Toluene) impacted material was collected and containerized in one(1) 85-gallon over pack drum and one(1) 55-gallon drum for transport and disposal. FCE personnel noted no further action was required on-site and crews demobilized.
